{
  "doc_id": "39561",
  "text": "Bortezomib is a proteasome inhibitor that has a suppressive effect on antibody production by plasma cells, stimulates apoptosis of this cell type, and decreases the number of bone marrow-derived plasma cells [CITATION_1] . Initially, it was approved for the treatment of multiple myeloma by the Food and Drug Administration and has now been introduced for use in KT and it is expected to show a stronger suppressive effect on humoral immunity than rituximab [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In an animal model, bortezomib effectively ameliorated glomerular, tubulointerstitial, and vascular changes of cAMR via the inhibition of antibody-producing cells [CITATION_4] . In the clinical setting, very few patients have received bortezomib as a rescue treatment for cAMR, producing inconsistent results. Hence, the therapeutic effect of this drug has not yet been proven [CITATION_5] . A randomized controlled trial to investigate the effects of bortezomib on cAMR (known as the BORJECT study) is now in progress, which can help determine the effectiveness of this drug (NCT01873157). ",
